text: Salome Buglass1*, Shannon Nagy1, David Ebert2, 3, Paulina Sepa1, Alan Turchik4, Katherine  L.C. Bell4,5, Fernando Rivera 6,7 and Jonatha Giddens4  1Charles Darwin Foundation, Av. Charles Darwin s/n, Puerto Ayora, Santa Cruz, Galápagos Islands, Ecuador  2 Pacific Shark Research Centre, Moss Landing Marine Laboratories, Moss Landing, CA 95039, USA  3 Research Associate, South African Institute for Aquatic Biodiversity, Private Bag 1015, Grahamstown, 6140, South Africa  4 National Geographic Society, Washington, D.C., USA  5 MIT Media Lab, Cambridge, MA, USA   6 Galápagos National Park Directorate, Av Charles Darwin s/n, Puerto Ayora, Santa Cruz, Galápagos Islands, Ecuador  7Instituto Nazca de Investigaciones Marinas, Av. 12 octubre 1615, Salinas, Santa Elena, Ecuador  *Corresponding Author: salomebu@gmail.com ORCID  0000-0001-6329-3937  Funding: This research was financially supported by National Geographic Society, Lindblad  Expeditions, MIT Media Lab, Ecoventura and Ms. Karen Lo  Abstract:   This study reports the first records of cowsharks (Hexanchidae) in the Galápagos Islands, in  particular Notorynchus cepedianus and Hexanchus griseus, observed between depths of 210  and 418 m on footage from free-falling autonomous deep ocean cameras. These sightings  provide new information on the habitat preferences and range distribution for N. cepedianus,  and the first records of H. griseus in Ecuadorian waters. Our findings support the formulation  of regional conservation strategies for these large apex predator species, and highlight our  limited biological knowledge of Galápagos’ deep-water ecosystems.Key words: Cowshark,  Eastern Pacific, Ecuador, Galápagos Islands, deep-sea cameras

The Galápagos Marine Reserve (GMR), covering approximately 138,000 km2, was  established in 1998 to protect the Galápagos archipelago’s marine biodiversity by banning  large-scale industrial fishing (Denkinger & Vinueza, 2014). Currently, the GMR is known to  be home to at least 57 chondrichthyans of which 33 are shark species (Acuña-Marrero et al.,  2013; Hearn et al., 2014). To date, no representatives of the cowshark family (Hexanchidae)  This article has been accepted for publication and undergone full peer review but has not been  through the copyediting, typesetting, pagination and proofreading process which may lead to  differences  between  this  version  and  the  Version  of  Record. All rights reserved. have been recorded in the archipelago. The Hexanchidae comprises three genera and five  species, characterized by having six or seven paired gill slits, a single dorsal fin, and an anal  fin (Ebert et al., 2017; Daly-engel et al., 2018).

The bluntnose sixgill shark, Hexanchus griseus (Bonnaterre 1788), is the largest member of  its family, reaching at least 5 m in length (Ebert & Mostarda, 2016) and distinguished by its  short blunt snout, broad mouth, and relatively small space between the dorsal and caudal fins  (Barnett et al., 2012). This species is widely distributed, found in the deep-sea, between 300- 2,500 m, from boreal to tropic regions (Ebert et al., 2013), along continental shelves and  upper slopes (Williams et al., 2010). In the eastern Pacific, this species has been recorded  from the Aleutian Islands to Baja California, and off Colombia and Chile (Ruiz-Campos et  al., 2010; Ebert & Mostarda, 2016), but never in Ecuadorian waters.   The broadnose sevengill shark, Notorynchus cepedianus (Péron 1807) is the only living  species of its genus. Reaching up to 3 m in length, the species is easily distinguished by its  seven paired gill openings, a broad head, large anal fin, and spots covering the dorsal surface  of the body (Barnett et al., 2012). This species is known to be distributed across temperate  coastal regions worldwide, except for the North Atlantic (Barnett et al., 2012). They are also  recorded in tropical waters off the Peruvian and Ecuadorian coastlines (Baerez, 1996;  Compagno, 2009), that experience seasonal cooling by the upwelling Humboldt Current  (Martinez-Ortiz et al., 2015). While most Hexanchidae representatives are deep-sea dwellers,  N. cepedianus is known to inhabit coastal waters, bays, and estuaries < 200 m deep (Ebert,  1996; Barnett et al., 2012) however, adults have also been found in deep-sea offshore waters  at depths ranging from  200-570 m (Stehfest et al., 2014; Weigmann, 2016).

During a study employing autonomous free-falling deep-sea camera devices (Turchik et al.,  2015) to explore deep-sea communities between 150 and 1500 m depth in the GMR, we  observed for the first time two species of cowsharks. The field campaign took place between  September – October 2019, on board the National Geographic Endeavour II, a passenger  vessel that visits most of the archipelago’s islands on a monthly itinerary. As the vessel is  only permitted to navigate to specific anchorage locations in the GMR, deployment sites  were limited to a 5 km radius of the anchorage and selected using a bathymetry map  (Carignan et al., 2017) to identify steep slopes or seamounts. These sites were accessed on a  zodiac, from which a total of 33 camera deployments were carried out for set periods of 3 to  8 hours at 16 different sites across the archipelago.  Developed by the National Geographic Society’s Exploration Technology Lab, the camera  instruments comprise a camera and computer system housed in a 76-cm diameter borosilicate  glass sphere with two external lamps rated to 6,000 m depth. The camera, a Sony Handycam  This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.

FDR-AX33 4K Ultra, captures high definition video with a 20.6 megapixel still image and a  viewing area between 2 and 6 m2 per frame, depending on the steepness of the slope on  which the camera falls. A PVC canister was attached externally carrying ~1 kg of yellowfin  tuna to attract scavengers. The camera instrument is positively buoyant and was weighted by  a 12 kg external anchor, giving it a descent rate of 1.5 m s-1. A programmed burn wire  mechanism releases the camera from the anchor, which then ascends to the surface, and is  located using a VHF transmitter. The devices had external pressure sensors attached to  measure depth, however, due to equipment failure, the depth readings were invalid.  Consequently, the depth for each deployment was derived from the bathymetry map layer   (Carignan et al., 2017). We calculated an error margin of ±22 m for these layer depths by  comparing them against known study site depths (n=16, depths ranging from 52-342 m) in  the GMR.

Two N. cepedianus were observed in one video recording taken 2.1 km north of Punta  Cormorant, Floreana (1°12.4026'S and 90°26.4174'W), at ~210 m depth over a predominantly  sandy substrate with a few rocky outcrops. Both sharks were identified as N. cepedianus on  the basis of their broad rounded head, single small dorsal fin, and spotted body (Figure 1).  The first individual was observed intermittently from approximately 7:10 am (UTC-6) over a  time interval of 29 minutes, during which it entered the field of view eight times. A second  individual was observed 20 minutes later making five appearances over an interval of four  minutes. Distinguishing markings on each shark made it possible to identify two different  individuals. Both sharks were observed swimming rapidly and appeared to nudge or bite the  camera device several times, sometimes causing it to shake dramatically from the contact,  during the intervals they appeared. A H. griseus was recorded 4.6 km north of Gardner Bay,  Española (1°18.6756'S and 90°43.3152'W) at ~418 m depth over a mixed substrate of sand  and rocky outcrops. Observed at approximately 8:30 am (UTC-6), the shark swam  intermittently in front of the camera for 3 hours, entering the field of view 23 times. Visible  cuts on its dorsal fin and medial left pectoral fin enabled us to determine that the same  individual was being observed during that period. The identifying features visible included  six gill slits, a posteriorly located dorsal fin, and a pale lateral line across its body (Figure 1).

From databases published (Tirado-Sanchez et al., 2016; OBIS, 2019) and unpublished  (Ecuador National Fisheries Institute), this sighting of H. griseus is the first in Ecuadorian  waters. Having a circumglobal distribution in tropical and temperate waters, and being  recorded off the Pacific coast of Colombia and Peru, this sighting in the Galápagos is  reasonable and expected. While there are bycatch records of N. cepedianus along Ecuador’s  continental coastline (Herrera et al., 2012), this is the first record of the species in the  Galápagos archipelago. Observing two individuals at the same place and time is indicative  that this was not a singular encounter, and could suggest the species might be a regular visitor  This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved. and/or resident in the GRM waters. As N.cepedianus is thought to predominantly inhabit  shallow coastal waters (Ebert, 2002), finding this species 1,000 km from the continental  coastline in deeper waters (~210 m) provides a new insight about their possible habitat range  in the Eastern Tropical Pacific (ETP).

Notorynchus cepedianus has also been found in the remote archipelago of Tristan da Cunha,  >2700 km from the nearest South African coastline (Caselle et al., 2018). These findings,  together with ours, are indicative that N. cepedianus also occurs in off-shore habitats,  supporting the notion that this species is capable of undertaking large scale movements  (Williams et al., 2012; Ketchum et al., 2017) and spends more time in deeper waters  (Stehfest et al., 2014) than previously thought. Although there is an active recreational and  scientific diving community in the Galápagos, to date there have been no reported sightings  in the shallow coastal waters of the islands. This could be indicative that this species is only a  seasonal visitor, or prefers deep-water in this region to avoid overlapping with other more  abundant large sharks occupying similar trophic positions in the islands’ coastal region, such  as Galeocerdo cuvier and Carcharhinus galapagensis. However, data (D.A. Ebert, unpubl.  data) from California and the west coast of South Africa and Namibia for N. cepedianus and  H. griseus indicates that the former occurs at relatively shallower depths (average <75 m)  than H. griseus (average >100 m).

Currently, very little is known about H. griseus and N. cepedianus populations in the ETP  apart from data gleaned from bycatch reports in Peru and Ecuador’s coastal region. Thus,  documenting and defining their occurrence and ranges is critical to formulating informed  conservation strategies and identifying key habitats for their survival (García et al., 2008;  Hearn et al., 2014). As apex predators, both of these species play a critical role in regulating  deep-sea and coastal habitats, yet like many deep-sea chondrichthyans, they are highly  susceptible to fishing pressure (Rigby & Simpfendorfer, 2015). According to the  International Union for Conservation of Nature, H. griseus is listed as “near threatened” and  N. cepedianus is categorized as “data deficient” (Compagno, 2009; Cook & Compagno,  2009), though there is evidence that the latter species is sensitive to fishing exploitation (De  Wysiecki et al., 2018).  While the GMR has seen a number of modern expedition cruises explore deep-sea habitats  (McCosker & Rosenblatt, 2010; Koenig, 2016; Cerutti-pereyra et al., 2018; Giddens et al.,  2019), their biodiversity remains largely undescribed. These findings contribute to our  understanding of fish biodiversity in the deep-water habitats of the GMR, and highlight the  importance of developing effective protective regulations for the deeper waters of the  Galápagos. These sightings underscore the likely presence of more unrecorded species in the  deep-sea zones of the region, including large apex predators.  This article is protected by copyright.
